omparative Analysis. Each category presents a question related to an article and\nthe corresponding ground-truth answer.\n25 Appendix I.1.\nWe begin by capturing screenshots of home pages and then refine these images by removing white\nmargins and other non-news elements to ensure the content focuses on news information, not\nadvertisements or errors due to website blocking. For analysis, we select a quiz model from our pool of\ncurrent most powerful commercial multimodal models, such as GPT4-V , Claude-3-Opus, and Gemini-\n1.5-Pro. We then guide the quiz model to progressively ask questions across multiple dimensions,\nincluding (1) basic understanding (2) contextual analysis (3) deeper and broader implications (4)\nfurther insights. The models design a Q&A set to address these dimensions. Subsequently, another\nmodel from our pool reviews and revises the questions for accuracy and relevance.\nThe final Q&As are then reviewed by humans for ultimate validation. To balance data collection\ncosts and user evaluation, we aim to gather about 500 questions monthly, selecting 100-300 for our\nfinal L IVEBENCH problem set, tagged with identifiers like LiveBench-2024-05 .\n4.2.2 Evaluation Metrics & experiments to enhance our\nunderstanding of model architectures and training data.\n2.2 The Evaluation Trilemma\nOur ultimate goal is to find a wide-coverage, low-cost, and zero-contamination way to evaluate LMMs.\nHowever, even with LMM S-EVAL, we find it to be hard or even impossible. Specifically, once we\nscale the evaluation datasets to 50+, it becomes time-consuming to perform a full evaluation run on\nthose datasets. Besides, those benchmarks are also susceptible to contamination during the training\n3time[ 79]. As shown in Figure 1, we believe there is a trilemma in model evaluation. One can not\nachieve the three goals simultaneously but only find a trade-off. The LMSys Chatbot Arena [ 13]and\nAI2 WildVision [ 50] are foundational works in stressing wide coverage and anti-contamination. We\npresent our solution to balance the other two sides of the triangle in Section 3 and Section\n\n            **Your Task**\n\n            Use only the Introduction above as your literature context. External paper databases, arXiv, author-profile APIs, and web search are not part of this benchmark.\n\n            1. **Context analysis**: Summarize the problem setting, prior approaches mentioned in the Introduction, and implied gaps you can infer from that text alone.\n\n            2. **Brainstorming**: Collaboratively brainstorm potential research ideas that build upon or address gaps in the Introduction.\n\n            3. **Summarization**: Summarize your collective ideas.\n\n            4. **Formulate a New Research Idea**: Develop a new research proposal in the format of the \'5q\', defined below:\n\n               **Here is a high-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning.**\n\n               **Here are the five core questions:**\n\n               **[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\n\n               Formulate the specific research question you aim to address. Only output one question and do not include any more information.\n\n               **[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\n\n               Explain the broader implications of solving this problem for the research community.\n               Discuss how such a paper will affect future research.\n               Discuss how addressing this question could advance knowledge or lead to practical applications.\n\n               **[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\n\n               Discuss the challenges and complexities involved in solving this problem.\n               Explain why naive or straightforward approaches may fail.\n               Identify any technical, theoretical, or practical obstacles that need to be overcome. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?**\n\n               Identify gaps or limitations in previous research or existing solutions.\n               Discuss any barriers that have prevented this problem from being solved until now.\n               Explain how your approach differs from or improves upon prior work. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n\n               Outline your proposed methodology in detail, including the method, dataset, and metrics that you plan to use.\n               Describe the expected outcomes. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n            Please work together to produce the \'5q\' for your proposed research idea.\n\n            Good luck!\n            '}, 'task_results': [{'agent_id': 'agent1', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction highlights the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs). The current landscape lacks a consistent evaluation protocol, with model publishers using custom pipelines that vary significantly in data preparation, output postprocessing, and metrics calculation. This variability hinders transparency and reproducibility.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- **Exemplary Works:** Some works have aimed to comprehensively assess models across various dimensions, but these are primarily language-centric.\n- **Custom Evaluation Pipelines:** Model publishers have developed their own evaluation methods, which often differ significantly, leading to inconsistencies.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Lack of Standardization:** There is no unified evaluation protocol for LMMs.\n- **Inconsistent Metrics:** Custom evaluation pipelines lead to variability in metrics and results.\n- **Scalability and Contamination:** Scaling evaluations to multiple datasets is time-consuming, and benchmarks are susceptible to contamination during training.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Unified Evaluation Framework:**\n   - Develop a standardized benchmark suite that encompasses a wide range of tasks and models.\n   - Ensure the framework is transparent, reproducible, and aligned with existing benchmarks.\n\n2. **Automated Evaluation Pipelines:**\n   - Create automated tools to streamline the evaluation process, reducing the time and cost associated with manual data preparation and postprocessing.\n   - Implement standardized metrics to ensure consistency across evaluations.\n\n3. **Contamination Mitigation:**\n   - Develop techniques to prevent contamination during the training and evaluation phases.\n   - Incorporate methods to detect and mitigate biases in the evaluation process.\n\n4. **Dynamic Benchmarking:**\n   - Create a dynamic benchmarking system that can adapt to new models and tasks as they emerge.\n   - Ensure the benchmark suite remains relevant and up-to-date with the latest advancements in LMMs.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe primary gap identified is the lack of a unified and standardized evaluation framework for large multimodal models. Current custom evaluation pipelines lead to inconsistencies and variability in results. Potential solutions include developing a standardized benchmark suite, creating automated evaluation tools, mitigating contamination, and ensuring the benchmarking system remains dynamic and relevant.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of large multimodal models (LMMs) is crucial for understanding their capabilities and limitations. However, the current landscape lacks a unified and standardized benchmark suite, leading to inconsistencies and variability in results.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nDeveloping a unified benchmark suite will enhance transparency, reproducibility, and consistency in evaluating LMMs. This will facilitate better model comparison, highlight weaknesses, and drive advancements in the field.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating a standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the variability in custom evaluation pipelines, the need for consistent metrics, and the time-consuming nature of scaling evaluations to multiple datasets.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious efforts have focused on language-centric models and custom evaluation pipelines, leading to inconsistencies. The complexity of developing a unified framework that addresses these challenges has prevented a comprehensive solution.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a standardized benchmark suite that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, ensuring wide coverage. Automated tools will streamline the evaluation process, and standardized metrics will ensure consistency. The expected outcomes include a transparent, reproducible, and aligned evaluation framework that enhances the understanding and comparison of LMMs.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent2', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction highlights the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite to evaluate large multimodal models (LMMs). Current benchmarks are fragmented, with custom evaluation pipelines that differ significantly in data preparation, output postprocessing, and metrics calculation. This fragmentation hinders transparency and reproducibility.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Exemplary works in language models have aimed to comprehensively assess models across various dimensions.\n- Custom evaluation pipelines have been developed by model publishers, but they lack standardization.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- Lack of a unified evaluation protocol for LMMs.\n- Fragmentation and inconsistency in existing benchmark suites.\n- Need for transparent, standardized, and reproducible evaluations.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Unified Evaluation Framework:**\n   - Develop a standardized benchmark suite that encompasses multiple tasks and models.\n   - Ensure wide coverage and reliability in evaluation metrics.\n\n2. **Automated Benchmark Generation:**\n   - Create an automated system to generate benchmark questions and answers.\n   - Use machine learning models to design and refine Q&A sets.\n\n3. **Bias Detection and Mitigation:**\n   - Incorporate bias detection mechanisms into the evaluation framework.\n   - Analyze and mitigate biases in open-source models.\n\n4. **Cost-Effective Evaluation:**\n   - Develop efficient methods to scale evaluation datasets without incurring excessive costs.\n   - Balance data collection costs and user evaluation.\n\n5. **Anti-Contamination Techniques:**\n   - Implement techniques to prevent contamination during the training and evaluation process.\n   - Ensure that benchmarks are free from biases introduced during data collection and processing.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe primary gap identified is the lack of a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models. Current approaches are fragmented and inconsistent, hindering transparency and reproducibility. Potential research ideas include developing a unified evaluation framework, automating benchmark generation, incorporating bias detection and mitigation, creating cost-effective evaluation methods, and implementing anti-contamination techniques.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of large multimodal models (LMMs) is crucial for guiding AI development. However, the current landscape lacks a unified and standardized benchmark suite, leading to fragmented and inconsistent evaluations.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite to evaluate large multimodal models (LMMs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nA unified benchmark suite will enhance transparency, reproducibility, and reliability in evaluating LMMs. It will facilitate fair comparisons among models, identify weaknesses, and guide future research and development in AI.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nDeveloping a unified benchmark suite is challenging due to the need for wide coverage, standardization, and reproducibility. Custom evaluation pipelines differ significantly, and creating a comprehensive and reliable framework requires addressing various technical and practical obstacles.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on developing custom evaluation pipelines for specific models, leading to fragmentation and inconsistency. The need for a unified framework has not been fully recognized or addressed until now.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a standardized benchmark suite (LMM S-EVAL) that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models. It will incorporate automated Q&A generation, bias detection mechanisms, and anti-contamination techniques. The expected outcomes include a reliable and reproducible evaluation framework that enhances the understanding and development of LMMs.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent3', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction highlights the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs). Current benchmarks are often custom-built, leading to inconsistencies in data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation, which hinders transparency and reproducibility.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Exemplary works in language models have aimed to comprehensively assess models across various dimensions.\n- Custom evaluation pipelines have been developed by model publishers, but they differ significantly, making it difficult to compare models fairly.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- Lack of a standardized evaluation protocol for LMMs.\n- Inconsistencies in evaluation methods across different models.\n- Need for a benchmark suite that ensures wide coverage, low cost, and zero contamination.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Unified Evaluation Framework:**\n   - Develop a comprehensive framework that standardizes data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation for LMMs.\n   - Ensure the framework is flexible enough to accommodate different types of multimodal data.\n\n2. **Automated Benchmark Generation:**\n   - Create an automated system to generate benchmark questions and answers, reducing the need for manual curation.\n   - Incorporate human validation to ensure the quality and relevance of the generated questions.\n\n3. **Dynamic Benchmarking:**\n   - Develop a benchmark suite that can adapt to new models and tasks, ensuring continuous relevance.\n   - Implement a mechanism to update the benchmark suite regularly based on new research and model developments.\n\n4. **Contamination Mitigation:**\n   - Design methods to detect and mitigate contamination in evaluation datasets.\n   - Ensure that the benchmark suite is robust against data leakage and other forms of contamination.\n\n5. **Scalable Evaluation:**\n   - Develop scalable evaluation techniques that can handle large datasets and multiple models efficiently.\n   - Use techniques like sampling and parallel processing to reduce evaluation time.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the introduction are the lack of a standardized evaluation protocol for LMMs, inconsistencies in evaluation methods, and the need for a benchmark suite that ensures wide coverage, low cost, and zero contamination. Potential research ideas include developing a unified evaluation framework, creating an automated benchmark generation system, designing a dynamic benchmarking suite, implementing contamination mitigation methods, and developing scalable evaluation techniques.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of large multimodal models (LMMs) is crucial for their development and deployment. However, the current lack of a standardized evaluation protocol leads to inconsistencies and hinders transparency and reproducibility.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nA standardized benchmark suite will enable fair and transparent comparisons among different LMMs, advancing the field by identifying strengths and weaknesses. This will also facilitate the development of more robust and reliable models.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating a standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the diversity of multimodal data and the need for consistent data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation. Ensuring wide coverage, low cost, and zero contamination adds to the complexity.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious efforts have focused on custom evaluation pipelines for specific models, leading to inconsistencies. The need for a unified approach has not been fully addressed, and existing solutions often lack the flexibility and scalability required for widespread adoption.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a comprehensive framework for standardizing data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation. An automated system will generate benchmark questions and answers, with human validation to ensure quality. The expected outcomes include a scalable, dynamic, and contamination-resistant benchmark suite that supports wide coverage and low cost.\n"}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "What is the lack of a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs)?",\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the field of AI by ensuring that evaluations of multimodal models are transparent, standardized, and reproducible. This will facilitate fair comparisons among models, help identify weaknesses, and drive further innovation. It will also enable researchers and practitioners to build upon reliable evaluation results, leading to more robust and effective AI systems.",\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Creating a unified and standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the diverse nature of multimodal models and the variability in existing evaluation methods. Custom pipelines developed by different model publishers often differ significantly in data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation, making it difficult to achieve consistency. Additionally, ensuring wide coverage, low cost, and zero contamination while maintaining high standards of evaluation is technically complex.",\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on language-centric models and has developed custom evaluation pipelines that lack standardization. These approaches have not addressed the need for a unified framework that can handle the complexity and diversity of multimodal models. The fragmentation and inconsistency in existing benchmark suites have hindered progress in this area.",\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed approach involves developing a comprehensive and standardized benchmark suite (LMM S-EVAL) that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models. The suite will include a diverse set of evaluation metrics and methodologies to ensure wide coverage and low contamination. The dataset will be curated through a rigorous process involving multiple models and human validation. Expected outcomes include a reliable benchmark suite that can be used to evaluate and compare multimodal models effectively, leading to improved model performance and transparency in AI research."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': []}, {'iteration': 2, 'task_assignments': {'agent1': "Given the detailed analysis and brainstorming provided, the next logical step is to refine the research idea and ensure that it aligns with the specific expertise and interests of 'agent1'. Since 'agent1' has a strong background in both quantum materials and AI, particularly in the context of Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) and their evaluation, we should tailor the research idea to leverage these strengths.\n\n### Next Task: Refine the Research Idea to Align with 'agent1's Expertise\n\n**Objective:** Refine the proposed research idea to better align with 'agent1's expertise in quantum materials, AI, and the evaluation of Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs).\n\n**Steps:**\n\n1. **Incorporate Quantum Mechanics and Materials Science:**\n   - Explore how quantum mechanical principles can be applied to the evaluation of LVLMs.\n   - Investigate the use of quantum-inspired algorithms or models to enhance the evaluation process.\n\n2. **Leverage AI and Machine Learning Expertise:**\n   - Focus on developing advanced AI techniques to automate and standardize the evaluation of LVLMs.\n   - Incorporate machine learning models to detect and mitigate biases in the evaluation process.\n\n3. **Integrate Behavioral Finance Insights:**\n   - Apply insights from behavioral finance to understand and address biases in LVLMs.\n   - Develop frameworks to assess the reasoning capabilities of LVLMs in financial contexts.\n\n4. **Develop a Unified Benchmark Suite:**\n   - Design a benchmark suite that includes a wide range of tasks and models, focusing on multimodal capabilities.\n   - Ensure the suite is transparent, reproducible, and aligned with existing benchmarks.\n\n5. **Incorporate Spectrum Sensing and One-bit ADCs:**\n   - Explore the use of one-bit ADCs and spectrum sensing techniques to enhance the efficiency and performance of the evaluation process.\n   - Investigate how these technologies can be applied to improve the sampling and processing of data in the benchmark suite.\n\n### Example of a Refined Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) is crucial for understanding their capabilities and limitations. However, the current landscape lacks a unified and standardized benchmark suite, leading to inconsistencies and variability in results. Leveraging quantum mechanical principles, advanced AI techniques, and insights from behavioral finance, we aim to develop a comprehensive and standardized evaluation framework for LVLMs.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) that incorporates quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nDeveloping a unified benchmark suite will enhance transparency, reproducibility, and consistency in evaluating LVLMs. This will facilitate better model comparison, highlight weaknesses, and drive advancements in the field. By incorporating quantum mechanical principles and AI techniques, we can push the boundaries of what is possible in model evaluation and open new avenues for research.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating a standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the variability in custom evaluation pipelines, the need for consistent metrics, and the time-consuming nature of scaling evaluations to multiple datasets. Additionally, integrating quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques requires significant expertise and innovation.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious efforts have focused on language-centric models and custom evaluation pipelines, leading to inconsistencies. The complexity of developing a unified framework that addresses these challenges and incorporates quantum mechanical principles and AI techniques has prevented a comprehensive solution.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a standardized benchmark suite that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, ensuring wide coverage. Automated tools will streamline the evaluation process, and standardized metrics will ensure consistency. Quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques will be integrated to enhance the evaluation process. The expected outcomes include a transparent, reproducible, and aligned evaluation framework that leverages quantum mechanics and AI to improve the understanding and comparison of LVLMs.\n\n### Next Action:\nRefine the research idea further by drafting a detailed proposal that includes the methodology, dataset, and metrics. This will ensure that the proposal is well-structured and aligns with 'agent1's expertise and interests.", 'agent2': "Given the context analysis, brainstorming, and summarization provided, the next logical step is to refine the proposed research idea and ensure that it aligns with your specific expertise in the intersection of large vision-language models (LVLMs) and behavioral finance. Since you are particularly interested in behavioral biases in these models, you can integrate this focus into the research proposal. Here’s how you can proceed:\n\n### Refine the Research Idea\n\n1. **Incorporate Behavioral Finance Focus:**\n   - Emphasize the importance of evaluating LVLMs in the context of behavioral finance.\n   - Highlight the need to assess biases such as recency bias and authority bias in these models.\n\n2. **Align with Existing Work:**\n   - Reference your recent work on behavioral biases in LVLMs.\n   - Discuss how your new research will build upon and extend your previous findings.\n\n3. **Develop a Clear and Specific Research Proposal:**\n   - Ensure that the research questions and methodology are well-defined and aligned with your expertise.\n\n### Formulate the New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of large vision-language models (LVLMs) is crucial for guiding AI development, especially in domains like behavioral finance. However, the current landscape lacks a unified and standardized benchmark suite that specifically addresses behavioral biases, leading to fragmented and inconsistent evaluations.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite to evaluate large vision-language models (LVLMs) in the context of behavioral finance, specifically focusing on biases such as recency bias and authority bias?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nA unified benchmark suite for LVLMs in behavioral finance will enhance transparency, reproducibility, and reliability in evaluating these models. It will facilitate fair comparisons among models, identify weaknesses related to behavioral biases, and guide future research and development in AI, particularly in financial applications.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nDeveloping a unified benchmark suite for LVLMs in behavioral finance is challenging due to the need for wide coverage, standardization, and reproducibility. Custom evaluation pipelines differ significantly, and creating a comprehensive and reliable framework that specifically addresses behavioral biases requires addressing various technical and practical obstacles.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on developing custom evaluation pipelines for specific models, often without a focus on behavioral biases. The need for a unified framework that specifically addresses these biases in the context of behavioral finance has not been fully recognized or addressed until now.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a standardized benchmark suite (LMM S-EVAL) that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, specifically tailored to evaluate behavioral biases in LVLMs. It will incorporate automated Q&A generation, bias detection mechanisms, and anti-contamination techniques. The expected outcomes include a reliable and reproducible evaluation framework that enhances the understanding and development of LVLMs in behavioral finance.\n\n### Next Task\n\nThe next task is to draft a detailed research proposal based on the refined research idea and the '5q' format. This proposal should include a literature review, methodology, expected results, and a discussion of the broader implications of the research. Once the draft is ready, it can be reviewed and refined further.\n\nWould you like to proceed with drafting the detailed research proposal, or do you need further assistance with refining the research idea?", 'agent3': "Given the detailed context analysis, brainstorming, summarization, and the formulation of a new research idea, the next logical step is to refine and finalize the research proposal. This involves ensuring that the research questions are clear, the methodology is robust, and the expected outcomes are well-defined. Here’s a structured approach to finalize the research proposal:\n\n### Next Task: Refine and Finalize the Research Proposal\n\n1. **Refine Research Questions:**\n   - Ensure that each question is concise and directly addresses the core issues identified.\n   - Make sure the questions are aligned with the overall goal of developing a standardized benchmark suite for LMMs.\n\n2. **Enhance Methodology:**\n   - Provide more detailed descriptions of the methods, datasets, and metrics.\n   - Include any preliminary experiments or pilot studies that can support the feasibility of the proposed approach.\n\n3. **Clarify Expected Outcomes:**\n   - Define specific, measurable outcomes that can be achieved through the research.\n   - Discuss how these outcomes will contribute to the field of machine learning and the evaluation of LMMs.\n\n4. **Address Potential Criticisms:**\n   - Anticipate potential criticisms or challenges that reviewers might raise.\n   - Prepare responses or counterarguments to address these concerns.\n\n5. **Draft the Proposal:**\n   - Write a detailed draft of the research proposal, incorporating all the refined elements.\n   - Ensure the proposal is well-structured and easy to follow.\n\n6. **Peer Review:**\n   - Share the draft with peers or mentors for feedback.\n   - Incorporate their suggestions to improve the proposal.\n\n### Example of a Refined Research Proposal\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of large multimodal models (LMMs) is crucial for their development and deployment. However, the current lack of a standardized evaluation protocol leads to inconsistencies and hinders transparency and reproducibility.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating large multimodal models (LMMs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nA standardized benchmark suite will enable fair and transparent comparisons among different LMMs, advancing the field by identifying strengths and weaknesses. This will also facilitate the development of more robust and reliable models.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating a standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the diversity of multimodal data and the need for consistent data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation. Ensuring wide coverage, low cost, and zero contamination adds to the complexity.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious efforts have focused on custom evaluation pipelines for specific models, leading to inconsistencies. The need for a unified approach has not been fully addressed, and existing solutions often lack the flexibility and scalability required for widespread adoption.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a comprehensive framework for standardizing data preparation, output post-processing, and metrics calculation. An automated system will generate benchmark questions and answers, with human validation to ensure quality. The expected outcomes include a scalable, dynamic, and contamination-resistant benchmark suite that supports wide coverage and low cost. The framework will be tested on a diverse set of LMMs and evaluated using a variety of metrics to ensure its effectiveness and reliability.\n\nBy following these steps, you can ensure that the research proposal is well-rounded, comprehensive, and ready for submission or further discussion."}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': "Result from the model:### Refined Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe evaluation of Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) is crucial for understanding their capabilities and limitations. However, the current landscape lacks a unified and standardized benchmark suite, leading to inconsistencies and variability in results. Leveraging quantum mechanical principles, advanced AI techniques, and insights from behavioral finance, we aim to develop a comprehensive and standardized evaluation framework for LVLMs.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite for evaluating Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) that incorporates quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nDeveloping a unified benchmark suite will enhance transparency, reproducibility, and consistency in evaluating LVLMs. This will facilitate better model comparison, highlight weaknesses, and drive advancements in the field. By incorporating quantum mechanical principles and AI techniques, we can push the boundaries of what is possible in model evaluation and open new avenues for research.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating a standardized benchmark suite is challenging due to the variability in custom evaluation pipelines, the need for consistent metrics, and the time-consuming nature of scaling evaluations to multiple datasets. Additionally, integrating quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques requires significant expertise and innovation.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious efforts have focused on language-centric models and custom evaluation pipelines, leading to inconsistencies. The complexity of developing a unified framework that addresses these challenges and incorporates quantum mechanical principles and AI techniques has prevented a comprehensive solution.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes developing a standardized benchmark suite that encompasses over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, ensuring wide coverage. Automated tools will streamline the evaluation process, and standardized metrics will ensure consistency. Quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques will be integrated to enhance the evaluation process. The expected outcomes include a transparent, reproducible, and aligned evaluation framework that leverages quantum mechanics and AI to improve the understanding and comparison of LVLMs.\n\n### Detailed Proposal\n\n**Objective:**\nTo develop a comprehensive and standardized evaluation framework for Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) that incorporates quantum mechanical principles, advanced AI techniques, and insights from behavioral finance.\n\n**Methodology:**\n\n1. **Benchmark Suite Development:**\n   - **Task Selection:** Identify and select over 50 diverse tasks that cover a wide range of capabilities, including vision, language, and multimodal reasoning.\n   - **Model Selection:** Include more than 10 prominent LVLMs, both open-source and proprietary, to ensure a broad comparison.\n   - **Data Preparation:** Develop standardized data preparation pipelines to ensure consistency across tasks and models.\n   - **Output Postprocessing:** Implement standardized output postprocessing techniques to ensure uniformity in evaluation results.\n\n2. **Automated Evaluation Pipelines:**\n   - **Data Collection:** Automate the collection of data for each task using one-bit ADCs and spectrum sensing techniques to enhance efficiency and performance.\n   - **Model Evaluation:** Develop automated tools to evaluate models on the selected tasks, ensuring consistency and reducing manual effort.\n   - **Metric Calculation:** Implement standardized metrics to assess model performance, including quantum-inspired metrics to capture unique aspects of LVLMs.\n\n3. **Bias Detection and Mitigation:**\n   - **Behavioral Finance Insights:** Apply insights from behavioral finance to understand and address biases in LVLMs, particularly recency and authority bias.\n   - **Bias Detection:** Develop frameworks to detect biases in the evaluation process, ensuring fairness and reliability.\n   - **Bias Mitigation:** Implement techniques to mitigate detected biases, improving the robustness of the evaluation framework.\n\n4. **Quantum Mechanical Principles:**\n   - **Quantum-Inspired Algorithms:** Explore the use of quantum-inspired algorithms to enhance the evaluation process, capturing unique quantum mechanical effects.\n   - **Quantum Metric Integration:** Integrate quantum mechanical principles into the evaluation metrics to provide a more comprehensive assessment of LVLMs.\n\n5. **Transparency and Reproducibility:**\n   - **Documentation:** Provide detailed documentation for the benchmark suite, including data sources, evaluation pipelines, and metrics.\n   - **Reproducibility:** Ensure that the benchmark suite is reproducible, allowing other researchers to validate and build upon the results.\n   - **Open Access:** Share the benchmark suite and evaluation tools openly, fostering collaboration and further research.\n\n**Expected Outcomes:**\n- A transparent, reproducible, and aligned evaluation framework for LVLMs.\n- Enhanced understanding and comparison of LVLMs through the integration of quantum mechanical principles and advanced AI techniques.\n- Improved detection and mitigation of biases in LVLM evaluations, contributing to the development of more robust and fair AI systems.\n\n### Next Steps:\n- Draft a detailed proposal that includes the methodology, dataset, and metrics.\n- Engage with relevant stakeholders to gather feedback and refine the proposal.\n- Begin implementation of the benchmark suite and evaluation tools.\n- Conduct pilot evaluations to validate the framework and make necessary adjustments.\n- Publish the results and share the benchmark suite openly to encourage collaboration and further research.\n"}, {'agent2': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session 5825e122-dfa1-4651-830d-619f599d5340", "full_chat_history": "In Session 5825e122-dfa1-4651-830d-619f599d5340 \\nFrom agent2 to agent1: Hi agent1, I have refined the research idea focusing on the intersection of large vision-language models (LVLMs) and behavioral finance, particularly emphas