 and reproducible evaluation framework that enhances the understanding and development of LVLMs in financial applications.\n\n#### 2. **Introduction**\n   - **Background:** Evaluating large vision-language models (LVLMs) in behavioral finance is crucial for understanding their performance and reliability in real-world applications. Current benchmark suites are fragmented and lack standardization, hindering transparency and reproducibility.\n   - **Problem Statement:** There is a need for a unified and standardized benchmark suite to evaluate behavioral biases in LVLMs, particularly in the context of behavioral finance.\n   - **Research Questions:** \n     - What is the need for a unified benchmark suite to evaluate behavioral biases in LVLMs?\n     - How can we develop a benchmark suite that addresses specific biases such as recency bias and authority bias?\n     - What are the key components of a reliable and reproducible evaluation framework?\n\n#### 3. **Literature Review**\n   - **Existing Benchmarks:** Current benchmark suites for LVLMs are fragmented and lack standardization. They differ significantly in data preparation, output postprocessing, and metrics calculation.\n   - **Behavioral Biases in LVLMs:** Previous research has identified behavioral biases in LVLMs, particularly in the context of finance and psychology. However, there is a lack of a unified framework to comprehensively evaluate these biases.\n   - **Gap Identification:** The need for a unified benchmark suite that addresses behavioral biases in LVLMs is not fully recognized or addressed in existing research.\n\n#### 4. **Methodology**\n   - **Benchmark Suite Development (LMM S-EVAL):**\n     - **Tasks and Models:** The benchmark suite will include over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, covering a wide range of scenarios in behavioral finance.\n     - **Automated Q&A Generation:** We will develop an automated system to generate benchmark questions and answers, using machine learning models to design and refine Q&A sets.\n     - **Bias Detection Mechanisms:** The benchmark suite will incorporate bias detection mechanisms to analyze and mitigate biases in open-source models.\n     - **Anti-Contamination Techniques:** Techniques will be implemented to prevent contamination during data collection and evaluation, ensuring that benchmarks are free from biases introduced during data collection and processing.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics:** Metrics will be outlined to assess model performance and bias susceptibility, ensuring wide coverage and reliability.\n   - **Data Collection:** The process for collecting and preparing data for the benchmark suite will be detailed, ensuring transparency and reproducibility.\n\n#### 5. **Expected Results**\n   - **Benchmark Suite:** The benchmark suite will encompass over 50 tasks and more than 10 models, providing a comprehensive evaluation framework.\n   - **Bias Detection:** The expected outcomes of bias detection and mitigation efforts will be outlined, highlighting the effectiveness of the benchmark suite in identifying and addressing biases.\n   - **Model Performance:** Anticipated performance of different models in the benchmark suite will be discussed, providing insights into their strengths and weaknesses.\n\n#### 6. **Significance and Implications**\n   - **Broader Implications:** The research will advance knowledge and lead to practical applications in AI and behavioral finance, enhancing the reliability and fairness of LVLMs in financial applications.\n   - **Future Research:** Areas for future research and development based on the findings of this study will be suggested, including potential improvements to the benchmark suite and further exploration of behavioral biases in LVLMs.\n\n#### 7. **Conclusion**\n   - **Summary:** The key points of the research proposal will be recapped, emphasizing the need for a unified benchmark suite to evaluate behavioral biases in LVLMs.\n   - **Call to Action:** Collaboration and 